ce:section.ce:para:
Cu,N,S-CQDs were initially designed through a one-step microwave-assisted hydrothermal method with the optimized condition (Figs. S3a–S3c). Under high temperature and pressure (Figs. S3d and S3e), the reactants undergo polymerization and carbonization phenomena, thereby accelerating the heteroatom doping process and resulted Cu,N,S-CQDs with exceptional optoelectronic properties than that of pure N-CQDs (illustrated in Scheme 1
                        ). Morphological studies of as-synthesized Cu,N,S-CQDs was performed using high resolution transmission electron microscopy (HRTEM) and fourier transform infrared (FTIR) spectra. As depicted in Fig. 1
                        a, Cu,N,S-CQDs exhibited quasi-spherical geometry and monodispersed particle distribution, with an average particle size of 4.99 ± 0.19 nm (Fig. S4). Furthermore, the HRTEM picture also revealed a crystalline structure of the Cu,N,S-CQDs having a lattice fringe distance of 0.206 nm corresponding to (200) facet of graphitic carbon (Fig. 1b). X-ray diffraction (XRD) analysis proved that the CQDs and Cu,N,S-CQDs produce a characteristics peak at around 24° (Fig. S5), which was well-matched with d-spacing information shown in Fig. 1b. These results indicated that Cu and S doping did not affect the carbon core structure of CQDs. FTIR spectroscopic measurement was conducted to examine the functional groups on the surface of N-CQDs and Cu,N,S-CQDs (Fig. 1c). The broad spectral bands in the range of 3000–3500 cm−1 was obtained for Cu,N,S-CQDs, which indicates the presence of O–H/N–H stretching vibration. Additionally, the IR bands observed at 1569 and 1354 cm−1 are attributed to the N–H bending and C–N stretching, respectively, indicating the existence of abundant amino groups on the surface of Cu,N,S-CQDs. Notably, C–S and S–H vibrations were also detected at 1304 and 2600 cm−1, respectively, suggesting the integrations of dopant ions into CQDs framework. Similarly, the IR spectra of pure N-CQDs reveals typical absorption band for -O-H/N–H stretching, CO stretching, CC, and CN bending vibration at 3000–3400, 1720, 1500, and 1450 cm−1, respectively. Moreover, the Raman spectra of Cu,N,S-CQDs revealed the crystalline G band, which is associated with the in-plane vibration of sp2 carbons, and the disorder D band indicates the presence of sp3 defects (Fig. 1d). The intensity ratio of the D- and G-band (ID/IG = 1.14) signifies the defect-rich structure caused by Cu, N, and S heteroatom doping. Pure N-CQDs gives two Raman signals at 1392 and 1587 cm−1, related to the D- and G-band structure. Based on the ID/IG ratio (Table S1), pure N-CQDs possessed highly disordered sp3 carbonic structure compared to the Cu,N,S-CQDs.
